Addressing this issue requires a multifaceted approach. First, mentorship programs should be expanded to pair young women with senior scientists who can provide guidance and counteract feelings of isolation. In my own life, I have learned the value of supportive networks; they keep one grounded amid uncertainty. Second, institutions must enforce transparent hiring and promotion practices, ensuring that evaluation criteria are merit-based rather than influenced by unconscious gender biases. Third, educational curricula should incorporate stories of female pioneers in science—figures who may not be widely known but whose work was foundational—to inspire students from a young age. Finally, society at large must shift its expectations: the notion that women should prioritize family over career needs to be challenged. Policies such as flexible working hours and parental leave for all genders can help balance professional aspirations with personal responsibilities.

